It wasn’t easy to get to the point where life felt better. I feel like no one talks about the grief involved in letting go of an eating disorder. When I decided to recover, I was at a point where I knew that my ED was not serving me. Yet, it was hard for me to imagine a life without it; I had spent so long stuck in those habits and thought processes, that it began to feel like the ED was a part of me…sometimes it even felt like it was me. Choosing to recover meant letting go of that part of my identity and learning what life looked like without it. My ED tried to convince me that life would be empty without it, but I’m so glad I didn’t listen. Even though it was scary and weirdly sad at times, I can confidently say that I’m having a better life without it ✌️

I wish I knew less about cross training, but, unfortunately, I’m a bit of an expert 🫠 here are my top tips ⬇️⬇️⬇️

1. Use the 10min/mile rule: for every mile you would have run, cross train for 10min. For example, if you would normally do a 5 mile run, replace that with a 50min cross train sesh. 

2. Use HR (heart rate) to gauge effort: HR while cross training is usually ~10bpm lower than if you were running, but this varies from person to person. I try to keep my HR within 10bpm of what it would have been if I were running. So, if it’s an easy day, I want my HR to be 135-145bpm. If it’s a threshold day, I try to keep it above 155, etc. 

3. Try to mimic running workouts: it helps me stay sane and feel like I’m maintaining fitness if I continue on my normal training plan, but convert the workouts to the bike or elliptical. Here are some of my faves: 

To mimic hills: 10-15x 45sec standing sprint on bike with 75sec rest between reps. I turn the resistance up and stand on the pedals; this allows me to have a high power output and muscular burn, just like I would on a hill rep. 

To mimic threshold: 6-5-4-3-2-1 on elliptical. For this one, the ‘ON’ and ‘OFF’ are equal duration so it’s 6min on, 6min off, 5min on, 5min off, etc. However, the ON reps are just over threshold (so about 80%), and the OFF reps are just under threshold (so about 60%). This one keeps your HR up but actually goes by really quickly, trust me! 

To mimic kilometer repeats: on the bike or elliptical 5-8x3min @ 90% effort with equal rest between reps. This tests your mental and physical endurance by sustaining a hard effort for quite a while, but allows you to recover well between reps. You can also mimic most track workouts by converting the distance to the amount of time that rep would have taken e.g. 400 reps=75sec repeats. 

I hope this helps anyone who is cross training due to injury or just replacing some miles with cross training. I think it’s a great tool and has huge benefits for building fitness!

It shouldn’t be a chore 🤷‍♀️

With the start of the new year, I notice so much of the emphasis on social media is discipline and commitment which I definitely value. However, I think that there is a lack of emphasis on enjoyment, excitement, and passion around the pursuit of goals. If pursuing a goal feels like a chore every day, and you’re constantly relying on discipline to take every step in that pursuit, it might not be the right goal for you. Obviously when setting challenging goals, the pursuit won’t be all rainbows and butterflies, but it should be fulfilling and enjoyable the majority of the time. In my opinion, discipline comes into play on “those” days when everything feels hard, but you know it will be worth it in the end. 

Choosing a goal that truly interests and excites you is so important because, if discipline or commitment is the only thing keeping you going, that isn’t sustainable. The process of chasing a big goal should be fun, and the whole “committed not motivated” narrative suggests otherwise. This is a little reminder that goals can be fun, as long as they’re the right ones for you 🤌

#goalsetting #enjoytheprocess #passion #joy #running

2021 was the hardest year of my life. I was simultaneously training for the Olympic trials and attending eating disorder treatment for 10hr/day. While many parts of this experience were absolutely horrendous (the 6AM wake ups, emotional turmoil, mental burn out, identity crises, etc), I can now look back and say that I am so proud of the way I navigated this time of my life. 

It was incredibly challenging, but sometimes the hardest times are when we experience the most growth, and that was definitely the case for me. Over the last week, I’ve gone back through my videos, journals, texts, and photos in an effort to create a YouTube video that encapsulates this experience. My main takeaways from this were a) I’ll never be able to fully articulate what it was like and b) it’s amazing to see how far I’ve come 

At the time, the struggle seemed like it would never end, but, looking back now, I know that my life has improved in so many ways because of the work I put in. If you are interested in hearing more about this experience, the link to my YouTube channel is in my bio. I hope this video can demonstrate that self-growth is worth it and that it is normal and okay to struggle 🤗

Also, a huge shoutout to my support system (you know who you are), I couldn’t have made it through without you ❤️

Injuries on the other hand take months to get through, hamper training and confidence, and never get easier to deal with 😭 Unfortunately, they are a part of the sport and something we have to learn to handle. 2nd race of the year and a 2nd place finish. Obviously not a win, but felt like a win for me. After my first race this year, my confidence took a big hit, and I struggled to understand why the fitness I saw in practice didn’t translate to competition. I just reminded myself that racing is a specific skill that takes time to hone, and, especially after not racing much the last few years, it will take more than one race to get it right (lol, obviously Allie 🙄) 

In this race, my goal was to stay as relaxed as possible the first half of the race and then push the last half and try to hunt people down and be competitive. I went through the 1 mile in 5th, the 2 mile in 3rd, and the finish in 2nd, so I felt good about my progression through the race. I still think there’s a lot of fitness and racing prowess to be built, but this was a promising step forward. Hoping to bring more confidence to the rest of my races this year and be willing to put myself on the line earlier with faith that I can push through to the finish. 

Anyway, this was a long way of saying I’m moving in the right direction but not there yet. Honestly I don’t know if anyone ever gets “there”, but the pursuit is absolutely lovely. If you read this whole thing, wow, your attention span is longer than mine.

It’s so much deeper than the surface. 

Struggling can look like: laying in bed, lacking energy, struggling with motivation, not having the desire to do anything, crying, pushing people away, etc 

BUT it can also look like: achieving big goals, excelling in school/sports/career, smiling, laughing, telling everyone you’re great, achieving more and more but still feeling empty, etc 

I think sometimes it’s easier to convince people you’re okay than to convince people you aren’t…which is dangerous. When was the last time you questioned someone’s generic “good” or “fine” response to the question “how are you?”. When you asked were you prepared to hear an answer other than “good”? 

It’s mental health awareness month. Take a minute to reflect on how you support the people in your life. Check in with them beyond the surface level, and try to understand how they are feeling. Sometimes being heard and validated can make a huge difference 💚

#mentalhealthawareness #mentalhealth

Consider this my formal petition against running-related injuries 🙅‍♀️🙅‍♀️🙅‍♀️ I know that they’re going to happen, but here are some of my best tips to avoid injuries. 

1. Run more of your miles uphill. Uphill running is lower impact and higher output, so you work harder but it puts less stress on your bones. A great way to do this is to run on the treadmill at a 3-5% grade, but you can also run up a long hill and get a ride down or do hill repeats and walk down between reps. 

2. Replace easy miles with cross training. You don’t have to replace every easy run with a bike sesh bc, let’s be honest, running is way more fun, but cross training can be a great tool to get in some aerobic training without the impact. Try replacing 1-2 runs a week with an XT sesh. I usually say that 10min of XT=1 mile running. 

3. Don’t be afraid to strength train, lift heavy, and build muscle. This will make you a stronger runner, and better able to endure the hard training. It can also correct imbalances and improve running economy 👏

4. Fuel. Being in an energy deficit increases injury risk and decreases adaptation to training, so make sure that you focus on consistently giving your body the energy it needs. 

5. Rest days are important. Rest allows your body to absorb all the training! Don’t wait until you feel overly tired or have some sort of pain to give yourself a day off. Regularly schedule rest into your training plan. 

Those are my main tips, but if you have any other input, I’d love to hear your injury prevention strategies in the comments 💪 👏

A mental reframe I’ve been working on. 

In running, so much of goal-setting is based around times, paces, and places, but that number-driven mindset hasn’t always served me. It leads me to believe that a bad race means that I failed. That I didn’t do enough, the training didn’t work, I haven’t improved, etc etc. 

In reality, so many factors contribute to the result on race day, and a bad race or performance doesn’t mean I am a bad runner or that my training was off base. Sometimes progress is made, but it takes a while to see that translate to results. That’s why I find it so important to stay process-oriented and remind myself to base progress on multiple metrics outside of just the place or time I get in a race. 

One of those metrics for me is effort. Yes, the effort that I put forth in a race, but also the effort that I put into my training day in and day out. The effort it takes to stay true to my goals and make decision after decision to support those goals. My effort is something that I can control 100%, and if I can cross the finish line knowing that I have done everything to prepare and execute my race to the best of my ability, I know that I can be proud, regardless of the result. 

#goalsetting #processoriented #progress #running

How to structure training ⬇️

If doing 2 workout per week: 1 threshold session every week and then alternate between VO2Max and Pace for the other session. Try to space the workouts 2-3 days apart. On the other days of the week, run easy, cross train, or rest. If possible, try to do one run during the week that’s a little longer (20-25%) than the others. 

If doing one workout per week: do a threshold session every other week and alternate between VO2Max and Pace for the other weeks. Try to have the workout on the same day every week so you’re equally fresh for it 😎. If possible, do a longer easy run (20-25% longer than normal) 2-3 days after the workout. 

Remember not to increase either mileage or intensity too quickly. So if you’re just getting started, do easy runs for a few weeks, slowly building up mileage. Then, try adding one workout per week and if that feels good, add another one a few weeks later! Always listen to your body and adjust training as needed for any aches/pains/fatigue/etc. if you’re not able to recover from the training, then you aren’t able to adapt to it. So take it slow, be intentional, and always always enjoy the process 🤗

P.S. the workout lists go in decsending order from easiest to most difficult (in my opinion), so start at the top and work down as desired 👏👏

What are your top predictions? 

Let me explain mine:

1. Full rest days: I think training will continue to become more and more polarized. So with double threshold workouts and the “hard days hard” mentality going strong, I predict that easy days easy will also rise to prominence. This already exists to some extent, but I think complete rest days will gain popularity and be a regular part of many elite runners’ training. 

2. High carb fueling: there is more and more evidence to support the use of intra-workout carbs for both performance and recovery. Cyclists have been pushing the boundaries with up to 120g carbs/hour. While I don’t think this is feasible for most runners, I do predict that more people will begin to utilize intra-workout fueling, even when training for sub-marathon distances, and that marathon and ultra runners will start pushing their intake higher. 

3. Training based on power: running pods that can provide power data are becoming more common, and I think this is a super useful metric that will gain popularity. Power has the ability to translate effort across terrains and conditions, making it a super reliable and versatile parameter to base workouts around. It has the potential to be more exact than paces or HR, so I think science-minded coaches will embrace it. 

4. Time trial marathons: track races have already gone in the time trial direction, with the fastest times of the year generally run in ideal-conditions, paced races that are specifically set up to chase standards or records. This year, McKirdy Micro Marathon showed that this same method could be applied to marathons with huge success. I think we’ll see more of this in the future, even with the large monetary incentives that road marathon majors offer. 

5. Heat training: obviously heat training has been utilized in the past to prepare for hot or humid races, but I think more and more athletes will use it as an additional training method, not just for specific race prep. Heat training has been shown to increase blood plasma levels and raise hemoglobin levels, both of which are advantageous in all conditions. 

I’d love to hear your thoughts and predictions in the comments!

How to structure training ⬇️

•1-3 easy runs per week from 20-60min long (can follow one of these with 4-8x15-20sec strides (flat or uphill)
•1-2 workouts per week; if doing 2, do 1 mile pace workout per week and alternate between threshold and VO2Max for the other workout. If doing 1, alternate between threshold, mile pace, and VO2Max, and as the goal race gets closer, you can start to do mile pace workouts a couple weeks in a row. 
•1 long run per week about 15-20% longer than your average easy run distance
•1-3 off days per week (can cross train or rest) 

As with any training plan, I would recommend slowly working into the training. Start with no workouts and just run consistently for 2-4 weeks. You can slowly increase volume by 10-15% per week. Then add one workout, and, once that feels sustainable, add another workout. Also, this is a rough guideline and you should definitely adjust it based on how you feel. For example, if the VO2Max sessions feel too frequent, replace some with threshold, etc. 

Finally, the workouts are listed from easiest to most intense, so start with the ones at the top!

easy days easy 👏👏👏

I used to be so fixated on running a specific pace on easy runs, convinced that I had to run fast all the time if I wanted to be fast in races. That isn’t the case at all, and running too fast on easy days can actually make you slower in the long term. If you want to be able to get the most out of yourself during workouts and races, you have to be recovered. That means allowing yourself to run at a pace that’s actually easy, not just an arbitrarily assigned “easy pace.” This pace will change day to day, and that’s okay! If it’s tough to allow yourself to truly go off feel, I’d recommend leaving the watch at home on easy days and just vibing 🤗
